  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations in Kentucky totaled $6.8B in FY2026 to date, with $103K as the average award size across 65,578 awards. Obligations fell 35.0% year over year. These totals are fiscal year to date and therefore partial for the current year. The Department of Defense accounted for $6.2B of obligations, making it the dominant buyer in the state. Direct Health and Medical Insurance Carriers received $4.6B in obligations, and HUMANA GOVERNMENT BUSINESS INC also received $4.6B. Several other buyers and vendors appear in smaller amounts: the Department of the Treasury awarded $161M, LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION received $451M, and THALLE - BAUER LLC received $320M. Top industries beyond health insurance include All Other Support Services at $452M and Other Heavy and Civil Engineering Construction at $341M. The FY series shows higher prior-year totals, including $12.5B in FY23 and $10.4B in FY25, with FY26 at $6.8B so far.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How concentrated is federal spending in Kentucky?",
        "body": "Spending in Kentucky is highly concentrated: the Department of Defense awarded $6.2B of the state's $6.8B in FY2026 to date. Direct Health and Medical Insurance Carriers accounted for $4.6B of obligations, and HUMANA GOVERNMENT BUSINESS INC received $4.6B, indicating a small number of entities and sectors hold a large share of obligations. Remaining agencies and industries distribute much smaller sums: the Department of the Treasury awarded $161M and All Other Support Services totaled $452M."
      },
      {
        "heading": "What does the FY26 to-date picture show compared with prior years?",
        "body": "FY26 to date totals $6.8B, below several prior fiscal years such as FY23 at $12.5B and FY24 at $12.3B. FY25 totaled $10.4B, so FY26 to date is markedly lower in comparison. Year-over-year obligations fell 35.0%."
      }
    ]
  },
